<h1>MongoDB Database &amp; Scalability Review</h1>
<p class="meta"><strong>Project:</strong> Node-js-CRUD-Generator (Multi-company POS + Accounts)<br>
<strong>Stack:</strong> Node.js, Express, Mongoose, MongoDB (single database)<br>
<strong>Review date:</strong> May 22, 2026<br>
<strong>Scope:</strong> Schema design, architecture, indexing, sharding readiness, production POS load assumptions</p>

<h3>Contents</h3>
<ol style="font-size: 10pt;">
  <li>Executive Summary</li>
  <li><strong>Database Architecture — Easy Guide</strong> (start here for non-technical readers)</li>
  <li>Collection Mapping</li>
  <li>Scores</li>
  <li>Sharding Analysis</li>
  <li>Collection-by-Collection Review (Technical)</li>
  <li>Single Database Policy</li>
  <li>Query &amp; Report Optimization</li>
  <li>Bottlenecks, Technology, Roadmap</li>
</ol>

<h2>1. Executive Summary</h2>
<p>This system uses a <strong>single MongoDB database</strong> with <strong>company_id</strong> on tenant-scoped collections. That is the correct foundation for multi-tenant SaaS.</p>
<p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Good tenant isolation and several strong indexes, but <strong>not shard-ready</strong> and <strong>not yet optimized for millions of invoice-heavy records</strong> without further work.</p>
<p>Primary blockers at scale:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Stock quantity derived by aggregating <strong>inventory_movements</strong> (no reliable live snapshot; warehouse_inventory model disabled)</li>
  <li><strong>Two parallel inventory ledgers</strong> (inventory_movements vs stock_movements)</li>
  <li>GL balances computed by scanning <strong>transactions</strong> on read</li>
  <li>Per-tenant order/PO counter hotspots and order number max-scan</li>
  <li>Offset pagination (skip/limit) on list endpoints</li>
  <li>Missing indexes on payment_receipt and user role-based listings</li>
</ul>

<h2>2. Database Architecture — Easy Guide for Anyone</h2>
<p>This section explains <strong>how data is organized</strong> in plain language. No MongoDB expertise required.</p>

<h3>2.1 The big picture (30-second version)</h3>
<div class="tip">
  <strong>One database</strong> stores data for <strong>many companies</strong> (shops/businesses).<br>
  Almost every record is tagged with <strong>company_id</strong> so Company A never sees Company B’s data.<br>
  The app is a <strong>POS (Point of Sale) + Accounts</strong> system: sales, purchases, stock, and general ledger (money ledger).
</div>

<pre class="diagram">                         YOUR APPLICATION
                    (Node.js + Express + API)
                              |
                              v
              +-----------------------------------+
              |   ONE MongoDB DATABASE            |
              |   (all companies live here)       |
              +-----------------------------------+
                              |
     +------------+-----------+-----------+------------+
     |            |           |           |            |
     v            v           v           v            v
  TENANT       SALES      PURCHASE    INVENTORY    ACCOUNTS
  (who)        (POS)        (PO)        (stock)      (GL)
     |            |           |           |            |
 companies    orders      purchase_    inventory_   transactions
 users        order_items   orders       movements   accounts
 branches                 purchase_    stock_       payment_
 accounts                  order_items  movements    receipts
 products
 warehouses</pre>

<h3>2.2 Multi-company (tenant) model — how isolation works</h3>
<p>Think of <strong>company_id</strong> as a label on every document: “this row belongs to Shop X.”</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Concept</th><th>Simple explanation</th><th>Where it lives</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Root company (tenant)</strong></td><td>The main business account. Other tables point to its <em>_id</em> as company_id.</td><td>companies row with <strong>no</strong> parent company_id</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Branch / child company</strong></td><td>A site under a parent (franchise, branch). Has company_id = parent’s _id.</td><td>companies collection (self-reference)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Logged-in user</strong></td><td>Staff, customer, or vendor. user.company_id = which tenant they belong to.</td><td>users collection</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Business data</strong></td><td>Orders, products, stock, GL lines — all carry the same company_id.</td><td>Most collections</td></tr>
</table>

<pre class="diagram">  PARENT COMPANY (Tenant)                    BRANCH (optional)
  companies._id = AAA                        companies._id = BBB
  companies.company_id = null                companies.company_id = AAA
           |                                          |
           +------------------+------------------------+
                              |
              All tenant data uses company_id = AAA
              (orders, products, transactions, ...)
                              |
              branch_id (optional) on orders, transactions, etc.</pre>

<p><strong>Rule for developers:</strong> Every API query for tenant users should filter by <code>company_id</code> from the logged-in user. The helper in <code>utils/modelHelper.js</code> sets this automatically on create/update.</p>

<h3>2.3 Five modules (what each part of the system does)</h3>
<p>
  <span class="module">1. Tenant &amp; setup</span>
  <span class="module">2. Sales (POS)</span>
  <span class="module">3. Purchase</span>
  <span class="module">4. Inventory</span>
  <span class="module">5. Accounts (GL)</span>
</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Module</th><th>Business purpose</th><th>Main collections</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>1. Tenant &amp; master data</strong></td>
    <td>Companies, users, branches, products, categories, warehouses, chart of accounts</td>
    <td>companies, branches, users, products, categories, brands, warehouses, accounts, attributes</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>2. Sales (POS)</strong></td>
    <td>Invoices / orders, line items, customer link, totals, payment on counter</td>
    <td>orders, order_items</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>3. Purchase</strong></td>
    <td>Buying from suppliers, PO lines, goods inward</td>
    <td>purchase_orders, purchase_order_items</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>4. Inventory</strong></td>
    <td>Stock in/out per warehouse; quantity history</td>
    <td>inventory_movements (main POS path), stock_movements (separate API)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>5. Accounts (GL)</strong></td>
    <td>Double-entry bookkeeping: debits &amp; credits, payments, expenses, adjustments</td>
    <td>transactions, payment_receipts, expenses, adjustments, amount_transfers, assets</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Support</strong></td>
    <td>Audit trail, auto numbering, alerts, integrations</td>
    <td>logs, counters, alerts, integration, process, blog</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>2.4 Entity relationships (who links to whom)</h3>
<p>MongoDB does not use SQL foreign keys; the app uses <strong>ObjectId references</strong> (same idea as FK).</p>
<pre class="diagram">  companies ─────┬──── default GL accounts (cash, sales, AR, AP, ...)
                   │
                   ├── branches (company_id → company)
                   │
                   ├── users (company_id, roles: USER | CUSTOMER | VENDOR | ADMIN)
                   │
                   ├── products ─── categories, brands
                   │       │
                   │       └── warehouse (via inventory_movements)
                   │
       SALES       ├── orders (invoice header) ─── order_items (lines)
                   │       │                           │
                   │       ├── customer_id → users       ├── product_id → products
                   │       ├── branch_id → branches      └── order_id → orders
                   │       └── payment_method → accounts
                   │
       PURCHASE     ├── purchase_orders ─── purchase_order_items
                   │       └── vendor_id → users (VENDOR)
                   │
       STOCK        ├── inventory_movements (in/out qty, cost)
                   │       ├── product_id, warehouse_id, company_id
                   │       └── reference → order / PO line / adjustment
                   │
       GL           ├── transactions (many rows per journal)
                   │       ├── account_id → accounts
                   │       ├── transaction_number (batch id, shared by lines)
                   │       └── reference_id → order | purchase_order | payment_receipt | ...
                   │
                   └── payment_receipts (Send/Receive money)
                           ├── user_id → users
                           └── payment_mode → accounts</pre>

<h3>2.5 What happens when you save a sale? (data flow)</h3>
<p>This is the <strong>most important flow</strong> for understanding the architecture.</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Create order</strong> (header) in <code>orders</code> — order_no from <code>counters</code>, totals on header.</li>
  <li><strong>Create order_items</strong> — one document per product line; subtotal computed.</li>
  <li><strong>Stock out</strong> — rows in <code>inventory_movements</code> (movement_type: out) per warehouse/product.</li>
  <li><strong>General ledger</strong> — multiple rows in <code>transactions</code> (debit + credit) sharing one <code>transaction_number</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Audit</strong> — optional row in <code>logs</code> (auto-deleted after 180 days).</li>
</ol>
<p>Steps 1–4 run inside a <strong>MongoDB transaction</strong> (<code>withTransaction</code>) so either everything saves or nothing does.</p>

<pre class="diagram">  [ POS Save Invoice ]
         |
         v
    +---------+     +-------------+     +----------------------+
    | orders  |---->| order_items |---->| inventory_movements  |
    | (header)|     | (lines)     |     | (stock out per WH)   |
    +---------+     +-------------+     +----------------------+
         |                                        |
         +------------------+---------------------+
                            v
                    +---------------+
                    | transactions  |  (2+ GL lines per journal)
                    +---------------+
                            |
                            v
                      [ logs ] (optional audit)</pre>

<h3>2.6 Customers &amp; suppliers (same table)</h3>
<p>There is <strong>no separate</strong> customers or suppliers collection. Both are <strong>users</strong> with different roles:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Role in app</th><th>role field</th><th>Used as</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Staff / cashier</td><td>USER</td><td>Login, permissions</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Customer</td><td>CUSTOMER</td><td>orders.customer_id</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Supplier / vendor</td><td>VENDOR</td><td>purchase_orders.vendor_id</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Platform admin</td><td>ADMIN</td><td>May omit company_id</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>2.7 General ledger (double-entry) in simple terms</h3>
<p>Each money event creates <strong>several rows</strong> in <code>transactions</code>, not one row:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Same <strong>transaction_number</strong> = one journal entry (batch).</li>
  <li>Each row is either <strong>debit</strong> or <strong>credit</strong> on one <strong>account_id</strong>.</li>
  <li>Debits and credits for a batch should balance (enforced in application logic).</li>
</ul>
<p>Account list lives in <code>accounts</code> (Cash, Sales, AR, Inventory, etc.). Company row stores <strong>default account IDs</strong> for automated posting.</p>

<h3>2.8 Inventory: two ledgers (important)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Collection</th><th>Used by</th><th>Status</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>inventory_movements</strong></td><td>POS order save, stock reports, COGS</td><td class="ok">Primary path — use this for architecture understanding</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>stock_movements</strong></td><td>Separate REST API (/api/stock_movement)</td><td class="warn">Parallel system — risk of duplicate/conflicting stock logic</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>warehouse_inventory</strong></td><td>Was meant to hold current qty per warehouse</td><td class="warn">Model disabled (commented out) — qty computed by aggregating movements</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Current stock formula:</strong> Sum(in movements) − Sum(out movements) per company + product + warehouse.</p>

<h3>2.9 All MongoDB collections (complete list)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Collection</th><th>Category</th><th>Has company_id?</th><th>Grows fast?</th></tr>
  <tr><td>orders</td><td>Sales</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
  <tr><td>order_items</td><td>Sales</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes (lines per order)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>purchase_orders</td><td>Purchase</td><td>Yes</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>purchase_order_items</td><td>Purchase</td><td>Yes</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>inventory_movements</td><td>Inventory</td><td>Yes</td><td class="warn">Very fast</td></tr>
  <tr><td>stock_movements</td><td>Inventory</td><td>Yes</td><td>Fast (if API used)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>transactions</td><td>GL</td><td>Yes</td><td class="warn">Very fast (2+ per event)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>payment_receipts</td><td>GL</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
  <tr><td>expenses</td><td>GL</td><td>Yes</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>adjustments</td><td>Inventory/GL</td><td>Yes</td><td>Low–medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>amount_transfers</td><td>GL</td><td>Yes</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>assets</td><td>GL</td><td>Yes</td><td>Low</td></tr>
  <tr><td>accounts</td><td>Master</td><td>Yes</td><td>Slow (chart of accounts)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>products</td><td>Master</td><td>Yes</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>users</td><td>Master</td><td>Usually</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>companies</td><td>Tenant</td><td>Sometimes (branches)</td><td>Slow</td></tr>
  <tr><td>branches</td><td>Tenant</td><td>Yes</td><td>Slow</td></tr>
  <tr><td>warehouses</td><td>Master</td><td>Yes</td><td>Slow</td></tr>
  <tr><td>categories, brands, attributes</td><td>Master</td><td>Yes</td><td>Slow</td></tr>
  <tr><td>logs</td><td>Audit</td><td>Yes</td><td>Fast (TTL 180 days)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>counters</td><td>System</td><td>No (key = order_no_&lt;companyId&gt;)</td><td>Tiny (one doc per tenant counter)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>alerts, blog, integration, process, complain, url</td><td>Other</td><td>Mostly yes</td><td>Low</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>2.10 Standard fields on most business documents</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Field</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
  <tr><td>company_id</td><td>Which tenant owns this row</td></tr>
  <tr><td>branch_id</td><td>Optional branch (orders, transactions)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>created_by / updated_by</td><td>Which user created or last changed the row</td></tr>
  <tr><td>status</td><td>active / inactive (soft business status)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>deletedAt</td><td>Soft delete (null = active); partial indexes ignore deleted rows</td></tr>
  <tr><td>createdAt / updatedAt</td><td>Automatic timestamps (Mongoose)</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>2.11 Target architecture (recommended future — for scale)</h3>
<p>Today the system is <strong>event-based</strong> (every sale appends movements and GL lines). For large scale, add <strong>snapshot</strong> collections (updated in the same transaction):</p>
<pre class="diagram">  TODAY (calculate on read)              FUTURE (recommended)
  -------------------------              ----------------------
  inventory_movements  ──aggregate──>    warehouse_stock_snapshot
       (many rows)                            (1 row per product+WH)

  transactions  ──aggregate──>         gl_period_balances
       (many rows)                            (1 row per account+month)

  transactions  ──aggregate──>         customer_balances
       (many rows)                            (1 row per customer)</pre>
<p>Sales and purchase <strong>header + lines</strong> design stays the same; only reporting/stock reads become faster.</p>

<h3>2.12 Technology stack (how pieces connect)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Technology</th><th>Role</th></tr>
  <tr><td>API</td><td>Express (routes/api.js, routes/admin.js)</td><td>HTTP endpoints</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Logic</td><td>controllers/*.js</td><td>Business rules, transactions, aggregations</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Data shape</td><td>models/*.js (Mongoose)</td><td>Schema, indexes, validation hooks</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Database</td><td>MongoDB (single database)</td><td>Persistent storage</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Shared helpers</td><td>utils/modelHelper.js</td><td>CRUD, pagination, company_id injection, search</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>3. Collection Mapping (Requested vs Actual)</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Business term</th><th>Model file</th><th>MongoDB collection</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Invoices</td><td>models/order.js</td><td>orders</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Invoice items</td><td>models/order_item.js</td><td>order_items</td></tr>
