</table>

<h2>4. Scores (0–100)</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Score</th><th>Interpretation</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Scalability</td><td class="score">58</td><td>Tenant field + header denormalization; ledger/stock paths dominate at volume</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Sharding readiness</td><td class="score">52</td><td>company_id everywhere; shard key and counter design need work</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Indexing</td><td class="score">62</td><td>Strong on orders/transactions/stock_movement; gaps on payments and users</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Future risk</td><td class="score warn">72</td><td>Higher = more risk (dual inventory, disabled warehouse_inventory, scan-based GL)</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>5. Sharding Analysis</h2>

<h3>5.1 Is the design shard-ready?</h3>
<p><strong>Partially.</strong> Queries typically include company_id. That is necessary but not sufficient for production sharding.</p>

<h3>5.2 Bad shard key choices</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Shard key</th><th>Problem</th></tr>
  <tr><td>{ company_id: 1 } only</td><td>Mega-tenant → one hot chunk; all writes for large retailer on one shard</td></tr>
  <tr><td>{ createdAt: 1 }</td><td>Global insert hotspot; cross-tenant queries scatter-gather</td></tr>
  <tr><td>{ order_no: 1 }</td><td>Not globally unique; poor distribution</td></tr>
  <tr><td>{ _id: 1 } only</td><td>Even writes but tenant queries need company_id → inefficient</td></tr>
  <tr><td>{ company_id: "hashed" }</td><td>OK for equal tenants; still hot for one huge tenant</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>5.3 Recommended shard key (most collections)</h3>
<pre>{ company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</pre>
<p>Reason: Application always filters by company_id; _id spreads writes within a busy tenant across chunks.</p>
<p><strong>Optional (branch-heavy POS):</strong> { company_id: 1, branch_id: 1, _id: 1 } — only if branch_id is always set on high-volume writes.</p>

<h3>5.4 Special case: counters collection</h3>
<p>Order and PO numbers use a shared counters collection (_id: order_no_&lt;companyId&gt;, $inc seq).</p>
<ul>
  <li>Shard key { _id: 1 } is fine</li>
  <li class="warn">Hotspot: every new invoice for one company updates the same counter document</li>
  <li class="warn">getMaxOrderSeqForCompany() scans all ORD-* orders — does not scale; remove in production</li>
</ul>

<h3>5.5 Cross-shard risks in application code</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Risk</th></tr>
  <tr><td>withTransaction (order + items + inventory + GL)</td><td>OK if all docs share company_id in shard key; fails if tenant field missing/wrong</td></tr>
  <tr><td>$lookup order_items → inventory_movements</td><td>Cross-shard join if collections shard differently — use same shard key</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Admin cross-tenant queries</td><td>Scatter-gather — avoid on hot paths</td></tr>
  <tr><td>skip/limit pagination</td><td>Slow on all shards at deep offsets</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>6. Collection-by-Collection Review (Technical)</h2>

<h3>6.1 orders (Invoices)</h3>
<p><span class="ok">Strengths:</span> Header/line split; lines_subtotal, total_amount denormalized; partial unique { company_id, order_no }; list index { company_id, order_status, createdAt }.</p>
<p><span class="warn">Risks:</span> Per-tenant counter hotspot; getMaxOrderSeqForCompany full scan; skip pagination; optional branch_id not indexed for lists.</p>
<p><strong>Recommended indexes:</strong></p>
<pre>{ company_id: 1, createdAt: -1, order_status: 1 }
{ company_id: 1, branch_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }
{ company_id: 1, customer_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }</pre>
<p><strong>Shard key:</strong> { company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</p>

<h3>6.2 order_items (Invoice lines)</h3>
<p><span class="ok">Strengths:</span> { company_id, order_id } index; validates company_id matches parent order.</p>
<p><span class="warn">Gaps:</span> Profit/P&amp;L uses $lookup to inventory_movements; no product/time report indexes.</p>
<p><strong>Add:</strong> { company_id: 1, product_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }, { company_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }</p>
<p><strong>Shard key:</strong> { company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</p>

<h3>6.3 users (Customers &amp; Suppliers)</h3>
<p>Customers = role CUSTOMER; Suppliers = role VENDOR (same collection).</p>
<p><span class="ok">Strengths:</span> Unique partial { company_id, email }.</p>
<p><span class="warn">Gaps:</span> No index on role; initial_balance without maintained running balance; balance views may scan transactions.</p>
<p><strong>Add:</strong> { company_id: 1, role: 1, status: 1, createdAt: -1 }</p>
<p><strong>Shard key:</strong> { company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</p>

<h3>6.4 inventory_movements &amp; stock_movements</h3>
<p class="warn"><strong>Critical:</strong> Two parallel inventory systems.</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Collection</th><th>Used by</th></tr>
  <tr><td>inventory_movements</td><td>Order save, COGS, stock checks, profit reports (controllers/order.js, inventory_movements.js)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>stock_movements</td><td>Separate /api/stock_movement with idempotency and line linkage</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Stock on hand = aggregate(in) - aggregate(out) over all movement rows. warehouse_inventory model is fully commented out but product controller still references it.</p>
<p><span class="ok">inventory_movements indexes:</span> { company_id, product_id, warehouse_id, createdAt }; { company_id, warehouse_id }</p>
<p><span class="ok">stock_movements indexes:</span> Idempotency, order_item uniqueness, product/warehouse/time — well designed</p>
<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Unify to one ledger; add idempotency to inventory_movements; maintain warehouse_stock_snapshot updated in same transaction as movement insert.</p>
<p><strong>Shard key:</strong> { company_id: 1, _id: 1 } | <strong>Archive:</strong> movements older than fiscal policy to inventory_movements_archive</p>

<h3>6.5 transactions (Ledger / GL)</h3>
<p>Multiple rows per journal (transaction_number shared) — correct double-entry pattern.</p>
<p><span class="ok">Indexes:</span> { company_id, createdAt }, { company_id, account_id }, { company_id, transaction_number, createdAt } (partial)</p>
<p><span class="warn">Risks:</span> 2+ rows per invoice; trial balance aggregates all lines; list-with-summary scans all matches then paginates; pre(validate) does 2-3 extra findById per insert; duplicate transaction_number field in schema (lines 43 and 79).</p>
<p><strong>Add indexes:</strong></p>
<pre>{ company_id: 1, account_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }
{ company_id: 1, reference_user_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }
{ company_id: 1, branch_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }
{ company_id: 1, "reference_id.module": 1, "reference_id.ref_id": 1 }</pre>
<p><strong>Pre-calculated balances (high ROI):</strong> account_balances, customer_balances, gl_period_balances collections updated on post.</p>
<p><strong>Shard key:</strong> { company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</p>

<h3>6.6 payment_receipts (Payments)</h3>
<p class="warn"><strong>Critical gap:</strong> No custom indexes — only default _id.</p>
<p><strong>Add:</strong></p>
<pre>{ company_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }
{ company_id: 1, user_id: 1, createdAt: -1 }
{ company_id: 1, transaction_number: 1 }
{ company_id: 1, payment_type: 1, date: -1 }</pre>
<p><strong>Shard key:</strong> { company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</p>

<h3>6.7 logs (Audit)</h3>
<p><span class="ok">Strengths:</span> Field size caps; TTL 180 days on createdAt; { company_id, createdAt } index; sanitization of secrets.</p>
<p><span class="warn">Risks:</span> High write volume if every API call logged.</p>
<p><strong>Shard key:</strong> { company_id: 1, _id: 1 } or ship to OpenSearch/S3 for search-heavy audit.</p>

<h3>6.8 accounts, products, purchase_orders</h3>
<p><strong>accounts:</strong> Unique partial { company_id, name }, { company_id, account_number } — good.</p>
<p><strong>products:</strong> Unique partial { company_id, sku }, { company_id, barcode } — good.</p>
<p><strong>purchase_orders:</strong> Same counter/numbering pattern as orders; { company_id, purchase_order_no } unique partial — good.</p>

<h2>7. Single Database for All Companies (Scale Policy)</h2>
<p><strong>Safe for most SaaS POS deployments</strong> when:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Every query includes company_id (enforced via req.user in modelHelper)</li>
  <li>Shard key includes company_id</li>
  <li>Mega-tenants (&gt;30-40% of data) get special handling</li>
  <li>Compliance does not require per-country physical isolation yet</li>
</ul>
<table>
  <tr><th>Approach</th><th>When to use</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Single DB (current)</td><td>Default; simplest ops; good to 100M+ docs with indexes/sharding</td></tr>
  <tr><td>DB per company</td><td>Rare; painful ops; only strict contractual isolation</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Hybrid (recommended at scale)</td><td>One cluster + archive DB for closed years + read replicas + Redis for dashboards</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>8. Query &amp; Report Optimization</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Report</th><th>Current behavior</th><th>Recommendation</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Invoice listing</td><td>handleGenericGetAll + skip/limit</td><td>Keyset pagination (createdAt + _id cursor); index { company_id, createdAt, _id }</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Dashboard sales/profit</td><td>$match + $group on orders/order_items</td><td>OK with company_id + date in $match; avoid $push all order_ids at scale</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Stock reports</td><td>Aggregate inventory_movements in−out</td><td>warehouse_stock_snapshot updated on each movement</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Customer balances</td><td>initial_balance + transaction aggregates</td><td>customer_balances snapshot + index on reference_user_id</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Trial balance / P&amp;L</td><td>aggregateTransactionSumsByAccountIds per account</td><td>gl_period_balances(company_id, account_id, period) nightly + on post</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Transaction list + summary</td><td>Full aggregate then find().skip().limit()</td><td>Facet or pre-aggregated period totals; date-bound all GL reads</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>9. Bottleneck Order (Busy Invoice-Heavy Tenant)</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>inventory_movements</strong> — writes + aggregate-on-read for stock</li>
  <li><strong>transactions</strong> — multi-line GL + full aggregations</li>
  <li><strong>order_items</strong> — volume ≈ lines × invoices</li>
  <li><strong>orders</strong> — counter hotspot + listing pagination</li>
  <li><strong>logs</strong> — write IOPS (TTL helps storage only)</li>
  <li><strong>users</strong> — later unless huge CRM search without indexes</li>
</ol>

<h2>10. Technology Recommendations</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Technique</th><th>Verdict</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Denormalize</td><td>Extend to running stock qty and account/customer balances</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Pre-calculate balances</td><td><strong>Yes</strong> — highest ROI for GL and AR/AP</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Redis</td><td><strong>Yes</strong> for dashboard KPIs, sessions; not GL source of truth</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Read replicas</td><td><strong>Yes</strong> for reporting/analytics routes</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Archive collections</td><td><strong>Yes</strong> for transactions, inventory_movements after fiscal close</td></tr>
  <tr><td>TTL</td><td>logs only (180d exists); never TTL-delete financial data</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>11. Hotspot &amp; Chunk Risks</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Risk</th><th>Severity</th><th>Detail</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Per-tenant counter $inc</td><td>High</td><td>Serializes invoice numbering per company at extreme TPS</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Mega-tenant on company_id shard</td><td>High</td><td>One chunk owns most of one retailer</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Jumbo chunks</td><td>Low</td><td>No large embedded arrays in orders; logs capped</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Write amplification</td><td>Medium</td><td>transaction pre-validate extra reads; dual inventory writes if both APIs used</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Cross-shard queries</td><td>Medium</td><td>Lookups and admin without company_id</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>12. Example Schema Additions</h2>

<h3>12.1 warehouse_stock_snapshot (new)</h3>
<pre>{
  company_id: ObjectId,   // required
  product_id: ObjectId,
  warehouse_id: ObjectId,
  quantity: Number,       // min 0
  updatedAt: Date
}
// Unique: { company_id, product_id, warehouse_id }
// Shard: { company_id, product_id, warehouse_id }
// Update in same withTransaction as inventory_movements insert</pre>

<h3>12.2 gl_period_balance (new)</h3>
<pre>{
  company_id: ObjectId,
  account_id: ObjectId,
  period: String,         // e.g. '2026-05'
  debit_total: Number,
  credit_total: Number,
  line_count: Number
}
// Unique: { company_id, period, account_id }</pre>

<h3>12.3 payment_receipt indexes</h3>
<pre>paymentReceiptSchema.index({ company_id: 1, createdAt: -1 });
paymentReceiptSchema.index({ company_id: 1, user_id: 1, createdAt: -1 });
paymentReceiptSchema.index(
  { company_id: 1, transaction_number: 1 },
  { partialFilterExpression: { deletedAt: null } }
);</pre>

<h2>13. Implementation Roadmap (Priority)</h2>
<ol>
  <li>Unify inventory — one ledger; deprecate duplicate API</li>
  <li>Fix or remove warehouse_inventory — align product controller with snapshot strategy</li>
  <li>Add missing indexes — payment_receipt, user.role, transaction period indexes</li>
  <li>Remove order max-scan — counter + unique index retry only</li>
  <li>Introduce stock and GL balance snapshots</li>
  <li>Replace deep skip with keyset pagination</li>
  <li>Enable sharding when hot collections exceed ~50GB — use { company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</li>
  <li>Read replica + Redis for reporting dashboards</li>
</ol>

<h2>14. Multi-Document Transactions</h2>
<p>Application uses mongoose.startSession() and withTransaction in:</p>
<ul>
  <li>controllers/order.js (order save/update)</li>
  <li>controllers/payment_receipt.js</li>
  <li>controllers/inventory_movements.js</li>
  <li>controllers/adjustment.js, amount_transfer.js, assets.js, purchase_order.js, stock_movement.js</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Requirements:</strong> Replica set or Atlas; keep transactions short; all documents should share company_id for sharded deployments.</p>

<h2>15. Files Reviewed (Codebase)</h2>
<ul>
  <li>models/order.js, order_item.js, transaction.js, stock_movement.js, inventory_movements.js</li>
  <li>models/payment_receipt.js, logs.js, user.js, account.js, company.js, product.js</li>
  <li>models/purchase_order.js, warehouse_inventory.js (commented out)</li>
  <li>controllers/order.js, inventory_movements.js, account.js, transaction.js, product.js</li>
  <li>utils/modelHelper.js (pagination, company_id injection)</li>
</ul>

<h2>16. Bottom Line</h2>
<p>The project has a <strong>solid multi-tenant shape</strong> (company_id, header/line split, partial unique indexes, bounded audit logs with TTL). It is <strong>not production-ready for millions of invoice-heavy rows</strong> until stock and GL stop relying on full ledger scans, dual inventory is resolved, and numbering/pagination are fixed.</p>
<p><strong>Do not shard on company_id alone.</strong> Use <strong>{ company_id: 1, _id: 1 }</strong>. A single database remains appropriate until mega-tenant or compliance requirements dictate otherwise — then prefer <strong>hybrid archive + read replicas</strong> over database-per-company.</p>

